* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ծառ}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|puu}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Baum|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|albero|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|[[ツリー]][[構造]]|tr=ツリーこうぞう, tsurī kōzo}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t+|lt|medis|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+|mk|дрво|n}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|drzewo|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|árvore|f}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|arbore|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|де́рево|n}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|mti}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|träd|n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|''(graphical user interface)'' tree list}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Baum|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|albero|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|ツリーリスト|tr=tsurī risuto}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t+|lt|medis|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+|mk|дрво|n}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|де́рево|n}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|mti}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|slang: marijuana}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|marihuana|f}}, {{t+|ca|maria|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|wiet|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|ruoho}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Gras|n}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|zioło|n}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|iarbă}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|трава|f}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|cần}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Woiwurrung: {{t-check|wyi|kalk}}, {{t-check|wyi|bajerrang}}, {{t-check|wyi|treang}}, {{t-check|wyi|tharang}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* [[Thesaurus:tree]]\n* [[:Category:Trees]]\n* {{l|en|arboreal}}<!-- irregular adjective form -->\n* {{l|en|dendr-}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{col3|en\n|firth\n|grove\n|holt\n|hurst\n|shaw\n|thicket\n|wald\n|weald\n|wold\n|wood\n|woods\n}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To chase (an animal or person) up a tree.\n#: {{ux|en|The dog '''treed''' the cat.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1897|editors={{w|Henry Howard, 18th Earl of Suffolk|Henry Howard}}; et al.|title=Encyclopaedia of Sport|location=London|publisher=Lawrence & Bullen|volume=I|page=599|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediaofs01suff\n|passage=When hunted it [the jaguar] takes refuge in trees, and this habit is well known to hunters, who pursue it with dogs and pot it when '''treed'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=w:Monte Dwyer|title=Red In The Centre: The Australian Bush Through Urban Eyes|publisher=Monyer Pty Ltd|page=146|text=\"And our dogs used to '''tree''' the cats on our property here, and we'd dispatch them.\"}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To place in a tree.\n#: {{ux|en|Black bears can '''tree''' their cubs for protection, but grizzly bears cannot.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To place upon a [[shoe tree]]; to fit with a shoe tree; to stretch upon a shoe tree.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''tree''' a boot}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1930|author=w:Dashiell Hammett|title=w:The Maltese Falcon|location=New York|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|chapter=14|page=165|url=https://archive.org/details/maltesefalcon01hamm\n|passage=Two suits and an overcoat hung in the closet over three pairs of carefully '''treed''' shoes.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To take refuge in a tree.\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to chase up a tree}}\n* Fijian: {{t|fj|vu ni kau}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|ajaa puuhun}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|עץ}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|enarbolar}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|ağaç}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to place upon a tree; to fit with a tree; to stretch upon a tree}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|sámfáz}}, {{t+|hu|kisámfáz}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====References====\n* {{pedia|Tree (disambiguation)}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Numeral====\n{{head|en|numeral}}\n\n# {{lb|en|colloquial}} {{pronunciation spelling of|en|three}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=eert|reet|rete|teer}}\n\n{{C|en|Trees|Recreational drugs}}\n\n==Afrikaans==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|af|nl|tree}}, syncopic form of {{m|nl|trede}}, from {{inh|af|dum|trede}}. Equivalent to a deverbal from {{m|nl|treden}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|af|/trɪə̯/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{af-noun|treë}}\n\n# {{l|en|step}} {{gloss|single act of placing the foot when walking}}\n# [[yard]] {{gloss|unit of length}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|nl|trede}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom syncope of {{m|nl|trede}}, from {{inh|nl|dum|trede}}. Equivalent to a deverbal from {{m|nl|treden}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/treː/|[treː]|[treɪ̯]}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-tree.ogg}}\n* {{hyphenation|nl|tree}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|eː}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nl-noun|m|treden,-en,-s|+}}\n\n# [[step]] {{qual|of a [[staircase]]}}, [[stair]]\n# {{lb|nl|archaic}} [[step]] {{gloss|distance of one step when walking}}\n# {{lb|nl|archaic|also {{m|nl|tred}}}} a unit of length of about 2 to 3 [[feet]], roughly equivalent to a [[yard]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|nl|traptree}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|af|tree}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nl|eert|eter|reet|teer|tere}}\n\n==Manx==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|gv|three}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|gv|sga|trí}}, from {{inh|gv|cel-pro|*trīs}}, from {{inh|gv|ine-pro|*tréyes}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|gv|/triː/}}\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|gv|numeral}}\n\n# {{cln|gv|cardinal numbers}} [[three]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:DIL|41872|head=trí}}\n\n{{C|gv|Three}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|tre}}\n\n==North Frisian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|frr|ofs|thrē}}.\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|frr|numeral}}\n\n# {{lb|frr|Helgoland}} [[three]]\n\n==Old Irish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sga-IPA|trëe}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|sga|prepositional pronoun}}\n\n# {{infl of|sga|tri||3s|f|acc}}: [[through]] [[her]]/[[it]] {{g|s}}\n#* {{RQ:sga:Glosses|Wb|2|c|4}}\n#*: {{quote|sga|Cain ro·noíbad Abracham tri hiris? In '''tree''' ǽm didiu fa nacc?|Hasn’t Abraham been sanctified through faith? '''Through it''' then indeed or not?}}"}}